across.text: Advance across delta by small boat
across.explanation: OVERDRAFT(i.e. a cash “advance”). Solution is OVER (i.e. “across”) followed by D (“delta” in the phonetic alphabet) and RAFT (i.e. “small boat”).

across.text: Maybe US criminals had briefly to be imprisoned
across.explanation: PERHAPS(i.e. “maybe”). Solution is PERPS (i.e. “US criminals”, short for perpetrators) wrapped around or “imprisoning” HAD once its last letter has been removed (indicated by “briefly”), like so: PER(HA)PS.

across.text: To start with alibi for example is a defence
across.explanation: AEGIS(i.e. a shield or “defence”). Solution is A (i.e. “to start with alibi”, i.e. the first letter of “alibi”) followed by EG (i.e. “for example”) and IS.

across.text: Distance often affected a proclamation from the French
across.explanation: EDICT OF NANTES(i.e. a sixteenth century “proclamation from the French”). “Affected” indicates anagram. Solution is an anagram of DISTANCE OFTEN.

across.text: Uncomfortable with allies failing to eat meal
across.explanation: ILL AT EASE(i.e. “uncomfortable”). Solution is an anagram (indicated by “failing”) of ALLIES wrapped around or “eating” TEA (i.e. “meal”), like so: ILLA(TEA)SE.

across.text: Glass changing hands in this checkout cart
across.explanation: TUMBREL(i.e. “checkout cart” – they were used to transport people to be executed. Also dung, just to rub it in). Solution is TUMBLER (i.e. “glass”) with the L and R swapped (indicated by “changing hands” – L and R being recognised abbreviations of “left” and “right”), like so: TUMB(L)E(R) => TUMB(R)E(L).

across.text: Working twenty-four hours? At first no – twelve
across.explanation: NOONDAY(i.e. “twelve”). Solution is ON (i.e. “working”) and DAY (i.e. “twenty-four hours”) with NO placed “at first”, like so: NO-(ON-DAY).

across.text: Put down duke, a powerful ruler, to be unmarried
across.explanation: DEPRESS(i.e. “put down”). Solution is D (a recognised abbreviation of “duke”) followed by EMPRESS (i.e. “powerful ruler”) once the M has been removed (indicated by “unmarried” – M being a recognised abbreviation of “married”), like so: D-EPRESS.

across.text: Relaxed, one’s agent finally very adequate
across.explanation: SATISFACTORY(i.e. “adequate”). Solution is SAT (i.e. “relaxed”) followed by I’S (i.e. “[Roman numeral] one’s”), then FACTOR (i.e. “agent”) and Y (i.e. “finally very”, i.e. the last letter of “very”).

across.text: Wickedness in dog suggested?
across.explanation: WRONGDOING(i.e. “wickedness”). The remainder of the clue plays on the solution, when written as WRONG DOING, being cryptic in itself, i.e. how DOING is an anagram (indicated by “WRONG”) of “in dog”.

across.text: He gambles debtor is concealing reserve
across.explanation: DICER(i.e. “he gambles”). Solution is DR (a recognised abbreviation of “debtor”) wrapped around or “concealing” ICE (i.e. a chilly nature or “reserve”), like so: D(ICE)R.

across.text: Leap to one’s feet and refuse to move
across.explanation: STAND FAST. Solution satisfies “leap to one’s feet” and “refuse to move”. Nicely worked.

across.text: Old woman’s herbal therapy?
across.explanation: MASSAGE(i.e. “therapy”). When written as MA’S SAGE the solution also playfully satisfies “old woman’s herbal”.

across.text: Bill tends to cry, in comprehensive victory
across.explanation: A CLEAN SWEEP(i.e. “comprehensive victory”). Solution is AC (i.e. “bill”, specifically a recognised abbreviation of “account”) followed by LEANS (i.e. “tends to”) and WEEP (i.e. “cry”).

across.text: Unwise to fail to fill in old exercise books
across.explanation: INEXPEDIENT(i.e. “unwise”). Solution is DIE (i.e. “to fail”) placed in or “filling” IN, EX (i.e. “old”), PE (i.e. “exercise”, specifically Physical Education) and NT (i.e. “books”, specifically the New Testament of The Bible), like so: IN-EX-PE-(DIE)-NT.

across.text: Being August, start to sweat on US borders
across.explanation: STATELINESS(i.e. “being august” – ignore the misleading capitalisation). Solution is S (i.e. “start to sweat”, i.e. the first letter of “sweat”) placed “on” or after STATE LINES (i.e. “US borders”), like so: STATE-LINES-S.

across.text: Thoroughly learn something for party that is of top quality
across.explanation: MASTERPIECE(i.e. “that is of top quality”). When written as MASTER PIECE the solution also satisfies “thoroughly learn something for party” – referring to someone’s party piece.

across.text: Each group of diners wants food so
across.explanation: EATABLE(i.e. “wants food so”). Solution is EA (a recognised abbreviation of “each”) followed by TABLE (i.e. “group of diners”).

across.text: Brave daughter, relatively short?
across.explanation: DAUNTLESS(i.e. “brave”). Solution is D (a recognised abbreviation of “daughter”) followed by AUNTLESS (i.e. “relatively short”, a play on how one maybe has an aunt missing).

across.text: Busy giving the pot this?
across.explanation: ASTIR(i.e. “busy”). When written as A STIR the solution also satisfies “giving the pot this”.

across.text: Judge member of cast going through lines uncooperative
across.explanation: REFRACTORY(i.e. “uncooperative”). Solution is REF (i.e. “judge”, specifically a shortened form of “referee”) followed by ACTOR (i.e. “member of cast”) once placed in or “through” RY (i.e. “lines”, specifically a recognised abbreviation of “railway”), like so: REF-R(ACTOR)Y.

across.text: Before Mailer, nothing American is unbelievable
across.explanation: PREPOSTEROUS(i.e. “unbelievable”). Solution is PRE (i.e. “before”) followed by POSTER (i.e. “mailer” – ignore the misleading capitalisation), then O (i.e. “nothing”) and US (i.e. “American”).

across.text: In defence, good for the French to drink wine
across.explanation: BASTION(i.e. “defence”). Solution is BON (i.e. “good for the French”, i.e. the French for “good”) wrapped around or “drinking” ASTI (i.e. “wine”), like so: B(ASTI)ON.

across.text: Reveller losing head: he’s waking others?
across.explanation: AROUSER(i.e. “he’s waking others”). Solution is CAROUSER (i.e. “reveller”) with its first letter removed (indicated by “losing head”).

across.text: Farm workers ending in embarrassment, colouring
across.explanation: PIGMENT(i.e. “colouring”). Solution is PIG-MEN (i.e. “farm workers”) followed by T (i.e. “ending in embarrassment”, i.e. the last letter of “embarrassment”).

across.text: Unworldly, one union trapped in cycle of decline?
across.explanation: SPIRITUAL(i.e. “unworldly”). Solution is I (i.e. “[Roman numeral] one”) and TU (i.e. “union”, specifically a Trade Union) both placed or “trapped in” SPIRAL (i.e. “cycle of decline”), like so: SPIR(I-TU)AL.

across.text: See lecturer in swimming pool here?
across.explanation: LEISURE CENTRE(i.e. “swimming pool here”). “Swimming” also indicates anagram. Solution is an anagram of SEE LECTURER IN.

across.text: Departs school, coming back famous
across.explanation: NOTED(i.e. “famous”). Solution is D (a recognised abbreviation of “departs”) and ETON (i.e. “school”) all reversed (indicated by “coming back”), like so: NOTE-D.

across.text: Compel men for cell to be stripped
across.explanation: ENFORCE(i.e. “compel”). “Stripped” indicates the solution has been hidden in the clue, revealed by stripping the surrounding letters of M(EN FOR CE)LL.

across.text: Oliver’s horse has smooth flanks
across.explanation: IRONSIDES(i.e. “Oliver [Cromwell]’s horse” – “horse” can collectively refer to a cavalry, a new one on me). Solution is IRON (i.e. to “smooth”) and SIDES (i.e. “flanks”).

down.text: Greek character and others one’s assumed nameless
down.explanation: ORESTES(i.e. “Greek character” who avenged the murder of his father by killing his mother. Games night was rough back then). Solution is REST (i.e. “others”) placed in or “assumed” by ONE’S once the N has been removed (indicated by “nameless” – N being a recognised abbreviation of “name”), like so: O(REST)E’S. One gotten from the wordplay, if I’m honest.

down.text: Magician left without female contrived to be mystifying
down.explanation: ENIGMATICAL(i.e. “mystifying”). Solution is an anagram of MAGICIAN LEFT once the F has been removed (indicated by “without female” – F being a recognised abbreviation of “female”). Nicely worked.

down.text: Put off find (not mine)
down.explanation: DETER(i.e. “put off”). Solution is DETERMINE (i.e. “find”) with the MINE removed (indicated by “not mine”).

down.text: Two equal parts? Not hard at all, with a fodder plant
down.explanation: ALFALFA(i.e. “fodder plant”). Solution is HALF and HALF (i.e. “two equal parts”) with the Hs removed (indicated by “not hard at all” – H being a recognised abbreviation of “hard” used in grading pencils) and the remainder followed by A, like so: ALF-ALF-A.

down.text: Drop of water shortly for plant
down.explanation: TEA(i.e. “plant”). Solution is TEAR (i.e. “drop of water”) with its last letter removed (indicated by “shortly”).

down.text: City in revolution at first pretty backward, rejecting both sides
down.explanation: PETROGRAD(i.e. Russian “city in revolution”, now known as Saint Petersburg, via Leningrad). Solution is P (i.e. “at first pretty”, i.e. the first letter of “pretty”) followed by RETROGRADE (i.e. “backward”) once its first and last letters have been removed (indicated by “rejecting both sides”), like so: P-ETROGRAD.

down.text: Live on the edge
down.explanation: RESIDE(i.e. “live”). Solution is RE (i.e. “on the” or regarding – think email replies) followed by SIDE (i.e. “edge”). Simple, but neatly done.

down.text: First Murderer’s speech: I make peers sick, drinking my soup – and the monarch
down.explanation: AM I MY BROTHER’S KEEPER?(response from Cain, “first murderer” in The Bible, when asked by God for Abel’s whereabouts after he’d done him in). Solution is an anagram (indicated by “sick”) of I MAKE PEERS wrapped around or “drinking” MY, BROTH (i.e. “soup”) and ER (i.e. “the monarch”, specifically Elizabeth Regina), like so: AMI(MY-BROTH-ER)SKEEPER.

down.text: Shame about horrible noise in tank
down.explanation: SALADIN(i.e “tank” created in the mid-1950s – more an armoured car with a turret stuck on top. Perfect for the school run). This took a while to twig, but the solution is ALAS (i.e. “shame”) reversed (indicated by “about”) and followed by DIN (i.e. “horrible noise”), like so: SALA-DIN.

down.text: Coming across page, not fond of Shelley? The exact opposite
down.explanation: ANTIPODES(i.e. “the exact opposite”). Solution is ANTI-ODES (i.e. “not fond of [romantic poet Percy] Shelley”) wrapped around or “coming across” P (a recognised abbreviation of “page”), like so: ANTI-(P)-ODES.

down.text: Serious wizard in Tyrone, say, worshipped figure
down.explanation: GRAVEN IMAGE(i.e. “worshipped figure”). Solution is GRAVE (i.e. “serious”) followed by NI MAGE (i.e. “wizard in Tyrone, say” – County Tyrone being in Northern Ireland, or NI).

down.text: Maybe young member of family has not got on flight
down.explanation: STEPS(i.e. “flight” of stairs). Solution is STEPSON (i.e. “maybe young member of family”) with the ON removed (indicated by “has not got on”).

down.text: Fail to understand why coin toss doesn’t produce result?
down.explanation: NOT MAKE HEAD OR TAIL OF. Solution satisfies “fail to understand” and “why coin toss doesn’t produce result”.

down.text: Regain consciousness, nearly safe following powerful shot?
down.explanation: SURFACE(i.e. “regain consciousness”). Another that took a while to twig. Solution is SURE (i.e. “safe”) once the last letter has been removed (indicated by “nearly”) and the remainder followed by F (a recognised abbreviation of “following”) and ACE (i.e. “powerful shot” in tennis), like so: SUR-F-ACE.

down.text: Spooner’s finest clothes not regularly seen at the bar
down.explanation: GUEST BEER(i.e. “not regularly seen at the bar”). “Spooner’s” indicates the solution is a Spoonerism of BEST GEAR (i.e. “finest clothes”).

down.text: One is taken in by a most peculiar philosophy
down.explanation: TAOISM(i.e. “philosophy”). Solution is I (i.e. “[Roman numeral] one”) placed or “taken in by” an anagram (indicated by “peculiar”) of A MOST, like so: TAO(I)SM.

down.text: Tug on left side circling southern approaches
down.explanation: DRAWS NEAR(i.e. “approaches”). Solution is DRAW (i.e. “tug”) and NEAR (i.e. “on left side” with reference to vehicles on roads, supposedly) wrapped around or “circling” S (a recognised abbreviation of “southern”), like so: DRAW-(S)-NEAR.

down.text: Sort of wave, going round one way in chapel
down.explanation: SISTINE(i.e. a “chapel”). Solution is SINE (i.e. “sort of wave”) wrapped or “going round” I (i.e. “[Roman numeral] one”) and ST (i.e. “way”, specifically a recognised abbreviation of “street”), like so: S(I-ST)INE.

down.text: Trees start off sale, unplanned?
down.explanation: MAPLESS(i.e. “unplanned”, playing on maps being plans). Solution is MAPLES (i.e. “trees”) followed by S (i.e. “start off [of] sale”, i.e. the first letter of “sale”).

down.text: Creature pouched in the afternoon biting us, very upset
down.explanation: POSSUM(i.e. “creature pouched”). Solution is PM (i.e. “in the afternoon”) wrapped around or “biting” US and SO (i.e. “very”) once reversed (indicated by “upset” – this being a down clue), like so: P(OS-SU)M. “Biting” is pushing it a little, IMLTHO.

down.text: Corrupt sheriff’s assistant half-cut at wild party
down.explanation: DEPRAVE(i.e. “corrupt”). Solution is DEPUTY (i.e. “sheriff’s assistant”) “half-cut”, making DEP. This is followed by RAVE (i.e. “wild party”), like so: DEP-RAVE.

down.text: Probable left-winger’s broadcast is fantastic
down.explanation: ANTIFASCIST(i.e. “probable left-winger”). “Broadcast” indicates anagram. Solution is an anagram of IS FANTASTIC.

down.text: Turned out and applied to keep most of treasure
down.explanation: EXTROVERTED(i.e. “turned out”). Solution is EXERTED (i.e. “applied”) wrapped around or “keeping” TROVE (i.e. “treasure”) once its last letter has been removed (indicated by “most of”), like so: EX(TROV)ERTED.

down.text: Made happy to have meal, if I must be in the garden
down.explanation: BEATIFIED(i.e. “made happy”). Solution is EAT (i.e. “to have meal”) and IF I all placed “in” BED (i.e. “garden”), like so: B(EAT-IF-I)ED.

down.text: Act with elegance on the radio, one admits
down.explanation: TURNSTILE(i.e. “one admits”). Solution is TURN (i.e. performer or “act”) followed by a homophone (indicated by “on the radio”) of STYLE (i.e. “elegance”), like so: TURN-STILE.

down.text: Large amount, definitely brother’s cut
down.explanation: TONSURE(i.e. a friar or “brother’s [hair]cut”). Solution is TON (i.e. “large amount”) followed by SURE (i.e. “definitely”).

down.text: Drink more extravagantly as commander
down.explanation: SUPREMO(i.e. “commander”). Solution is SUP (i.e. “drink”) followed by an anagram (indicated by “extravagantly”) of MORE, like so: SUP-REMO.

down.text: Subjects for painting that shouldn’t be dropped
down.explanation: SITTERS. Solution satisfies “subjects for painting” and, I guess, “that shouldn’t be dropped”.One I’m not 100% on, as SITTERS in my view (and that of Chambers) are easy shots such as open goals in football, i.e. something that requires an offensive action. I’m not convinced that the word extends to ball games that involve catching, e.g. fly balls in baseball or in cricket. I don’t know, maybe Bumble said it once.[EDIT: My Oxford expands on Chambers, defining a sitter as an easy shot or catch. Thanks to all the commenters below for baring their souls. 😀 For the record, I have all the hand-eye coordination of Captain Hook on a trampoline. – LP]

down.text: Monkey’s mistake
down.explanation: HOWLER. Solution satisfies “monkey”, specifically one found in South America, and “mistake”. Chalk one to my Bradford’s.

down.text: Perhaps Higgs’ two children, one missing a sex chromosome
down.explanation: BOSON(i.e. “perhaps Higgs’” – referring to the Higgs Boson, sometimes referred to as “the God particle”). Solution is BOY and SON (i.e. “two children”) with the Y removed (indicated by “one missing a sex chromosome”).

down.text: Assume visitors are short of time
down.explanation: GUESS(i.e. “assume”). Solution is GUESTS (i.e. “visitors”) once the T has been removed (indicated by “short of time” – T being a recognised abbreviation of “time”).

down.text: Someone other than me, as it were, educated here?
down.explanation: UNI(i.e. “educated here”, a shortened form of “university”). When read as UN-I the solution also satisfies “someone other than me, as it were”, UN- being a prefix denoting “not”. Not-I, un-I, you get the I-dea.
